gling to hold on to their family wealth by manipulating the government and people through secret councils and a figure-head doge. In 1844, Cooper called it "in spirit, the most American book I ever wrote" because of its depiction of the masses duped by demagoguery and the attempts of Congress to rein in President Jackson, who Cooper saw as representing the popular will. In the novel, the low-born hero, Jacopo Frontoni, is forced to become an agent of the state because his unjustly imprisoned father languishes in the infamous state prison. On the last page, Jacopo is executed as a scapegoat for the crimes attributed to him of which he is innocent, rendering his beloved insane. Only in a subplot does a noble couple escape Venice to enjoy marriage.The present text is based on all extant manuscript witnesses (including a lengthy deleted section) and offers extensive explanatory notes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 4aGeneral Interest : Fiction. 4aLiterature : American Literature. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aSappenfield, James A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchachterle, Lance, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSeymour House, Kay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849498240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438494982423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438494982/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles